Demon character for warmaster both with and without supports using Schlossbauer's awesome twigblight. I initially wanted to use this as a greater demon, but seeing the size of the forest dragon treeman I needed another model to fill that role. I'm going to use this one as my general instead. Yes, it's obviously a tree thing, but just imagine what it looks like if you paint the torso bone-y and the arms/legs bloody (or find my post on the warmaster revolution facebook to see my actual paint job).

10mm demon army
See my collections for the other units; I have a unit for each of the roles in warmaster revolution and a couple of heroes. Note that this army does not inherently match one of the big four chaos gods by design, as I find them dreadfully boring.

Supports
The supports are auto generated by Prusa. Nothing much to it.

Why?
I just got a 3d printer and was looking to get into warmaster with some friends when I noticed that there is no ready to print demon army yet. Given my 0-level modelling skills I instead decided to use existing models to create the army; this unit is one of the outcomes of this project.

Disclaimer
To be sure: none of these models are actually mine. I am a complete hack blundering his way through blender; all I can do is resize models, fatten segments and add cylinders (you may spot some of my handiwork on other models, or here!).

These 15 player character models are collected from various free posts we've made over the years, and come with character record sheets for our [CRUX roleplaying system, which is available as a free download from our own site](http://www.illgottengames.net/cruxuniversalroleplaying), as well as rules for [Pocket-Tactics](http://www.illgottengames.net/pocket-tactics) (our 3d pint-and-play strategy board game) and [Open-Tactics](http://www.illgottengames.net/opentactics) (our open-source, miniatures-agnostic wargaming rules).

All models are supplied without bases and print 100% support free. Daring Delvers are scaled for standard miniature gaming (30mm scale), and 15mm versions are included as well! Blank bases are included for both scales and, if you want a quick tutorial on adding them before printing, [check out this video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HGCwjUJVZ-0).

For those of you thinking about [supporting us on Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/illgottengames?fan_landing=true), our patrons get special weekly model releases, access to new storefront releases and our entire back catalog, plus licensing options to sell printed versions of our designs.

We at Ill Gotten Games are big fans of the [Vintage RPG Podcast](https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/unwinnable-3/the-vintage-rpg-podcast), and after designing a model for Hambone [the hammer-wielding ranger, Johan](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3483772)), I made one for Stu as well. This is Greel, an opportunistic (but deep down, gold-hearted) ex-mercenary company leader/current warlock with a magic ring that can turn him into a tree at the first sight of danger. The model prints without support.

If you haven't checked it out, Hambone and Stu (Horvath, from [unwinnable.com](https://unwinnable.com/)) do a weekly podcast where they discuss tabletop games, and do deep dives into RPGs old and new. This all branches off of Stu's excellent [Instagram feed](https://www.instagram.com/vintagerpg/?hl=en), which is always an insightful read if you're into the history and current state of tabletop roleplaying games. We're proud to be [supporting them on Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/vintagerpg/overview), and you should really check out what they're doing/throw them some bones if you like it as much as we do.

We're currently running a Kickstarter campaign for the [extended range of our ScatterBlocks](https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/292543184/scatterblocks) (quick-assembling miniature terrain), so drop on by and drop us a pledge if you want the full range.
